06120nam a2200793Ia 9780823271573DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1302164848  a97808232715737 a10.1515/97808232715732doi  a(DE-B1597)623952  a(OCoLC)1301549990  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aTRU0030002bisacsh04a364.106/60974723090432231 aWhalen, Robert Weldon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMurder, Inc., and the Moral Life :bGangsters and Gangbusters in La Guardia's New York /cRobert Weldon Whalen. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Characters -- tPrologue: Naked City -- t1 Reel Gangsters—Mobsters and the Movies -- t2 Real Gangsters: Abe Reles and the Origins of Murder, Inc. -- t3 Gangster City -- t4 Fiorello La Guardia and the Cinema of Redemption -- t5 Gangbuster: Thomas Dewey and Imperfect Justice -- t6 Murder, Inc.: “I Got Used to It” -- t7 A Theater of Ethics: Mr. Arsenic and the Murder, Inc., Trials -- t8 Ethics of Ambiguity: The Canary Could Sing but Couldn’t Fly -- tEpilogue: “That Dangerous and Sad City of the Imagination” -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1940 and 1941 a group of ruthless gangsters from Brooklyn’s Brownsville neighborhood became the focus of media frenzy when they—dubbed “Murder Inc.,” by New York World-Telegram reporter Harry Feeney—were tried for murder. It is estimated that collectively they killed hundreds of people during a reign of terror that lasted from 1931 to 1940. As the trial played out to a packed courtroom, shocked spectators gasped at the outrageous revelations made by gang leader Abe “Kid Twist” Reles and his pack of criminal accomplices.News of the trial proliferated throughout the country; at times it received more newspaper coverage than the unabated war being waged overseas. The heinous crimes attributed to Murder, Inc., included not only murder and torture but also auto theft, burglary, assaults, robberies, fencing stolen goods, distribution of illegal drugs,and just about any “illegal activity from which a revenue could be derived.” When the trial finally came to a stunning unresolved conclusion in November 1941, newspapers generated record headlines.Once the trial was over, tales of the Murder, Inc., gang became legendary, spawning countless books and memoirs and providing inspiration for the Hollywood gangster-movie genre. These men were fearsome brutes with an astonishing ability to wield power. People were fascinated by the “gangster” figure, which had become a symbol for moral evil and contempt and whose popularity showed no signs of abating. As both a study in criminal behavior and a cultural fascination that continues to permeate modern society, the reverberations of “Murder, Inc.” are profound, including references in contemporary mass media.The Murder, Inc., story is as much a tale of morality as it is a gangster history, and Murder, Inc., and the Moral Life by Robert Whalen meshes both topics clearly and meticulously, relating the gangster phenomenon to modern moral theory. Each chapter covers an aspect of the Murder, Inc., case and reflects on its ethical elements and consequences. Whalen delves into the background of the criminals involved, their motives, and the violent death that surrounded them; New York City’s immigrant gang culture and its role as “Gangster City”; fiery politicians Fiorello La Guardia and Thomas E. Dewey and the choices they made to clean up the city; andthe role of the gangster in popular culture and how it relates to “real life.” Whalen puts a fresh spin on the two topics, providing a vivid narrative with both historical and moral perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCrimezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aGangsterszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aOrganized crimezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aNew York City & Regional. 4aSociology. 7aTRUE CRIME / Organized Crime.2bisacsh  aAbe Reles.  aBurton Turkus.  aCharlie "Lucky" Luciano.  aFiorello La Guardia.  aGangster Films.  aGangsters.  aInc.  aJack "Legs" Diamond.  aMurder.  aThomas E. Dewey.  aprohibition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311072902340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327157340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823271573423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823271573/original  a978-3-11-072902-3  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles